{{for|the steamship|SS Dollart}} [[File:Dollart.png|thumb|Dollart and its surrounding area]]
The '''Dollart''' (German name) or '''Dollard''' (Dutch name) is a [[bay]] in the [[Wadden Sea]] between the northern [[Netherlands]] and [[Germany]], on the west side of the [[estuary]] of the [[Ems (river)|Ems]] river. Most of it dries at [[low tide]]. Many water birds feed there.
== Gaining from and losing to the sea == <!-- doesn't fit in the article -- [[File:Verdronken Dollarddorpen - Emmius, 1630.jpg|thumb|upright|The area of the Dollart before its creation. The villages shown disappeared as the Dollart bay expanded. (The map was drawn in 1630, after the Dollart had already reached its largest surface.)]] --> [[File:Dollart-Geschichte.png|thumb|Recovery of the fringes of the Dollart: polders on the German (right and top) and Dutch (left and bottom) sides]]
The Dollart Bay was created by a catastrophic storm surge in 1277,<ref>{{cite book |last=Goffart |first1=Walter |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qex4Pl0YATwC&pg=PA126&lpg=PA126&dq=dollart+ems+flood+1277 |title=Historical Atlases: The First Three Hundred Years, 1570-1870 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |year=2003 |page=126 |accessdate=2018-09-16 }}</ref> covering the district of [[Reiderland#The old Reiderland|Reiderland]] and large parts of the [[Oldambt (region)|Oldambt]] district. The flood inundated 43 parishes, and is estimated to have caused 80,000 deaths.<ref>{{cite book |last=Suess |first1=Edward |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RmkAAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA417&lpg=PA417&dq=dollart+ems+flood+1277 |title=The Face of the Earth |publisher=Clarendon Press |year=1906 |page=417 |accessdate=2018-09-16 }}</ref> Another storm surge in 1509 further extended the Dollart, flooding 30 more villages,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.verdronkengeschiedenis.nl/nl/stormvloed/stormvloed.html#symposium |title= “Stormvloed 1509” - een Nederlands – Duits cultuurhistorisch project |language=Dutch |trans-title="Stormvloed 1509" - a Dutch-German cultural-historical project |work=Stichting Verdronken Geschiedenis |date=2009 |accessdate=2018-09-16 }}</ref> and by 1520 the Dollart had its largest extension. Between the 16th and the 20th centuries, two thirds of the drowned area was reclaimed again.
Nowadays the unembanked forelands have been declared world natural heritage, as they are a paradise for all kinds of [[bird]]s and other aquatic species.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1314 |title=Wadden Sea |work=World Heritage Center |publisher=UNESCO |accessdate=2018-09-16 }}</ref>
== Border dispute == [[File:Dutch-German Border dispute.svg|thumb|Disputed border between Germany and the Netherlands]]
The Netherlands and Germany do not agree on the exact course of the border through the bay,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geodaten.niedersachsen.de/viewer_dienste/layerstruktur/layer-nordsee---ems-dollart-vertrag-25327.html |title=Layer Nordsee - Ems-Dollart-Vertrag |language=German |publisher=[[Lower Saxony|State of Lower Saxony]] |accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref> yet they have [[Agree to disagree|agreed to disagree]] by signing a treaty in 1960, laying out mutual responsibilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wetten.overheid.nl/BWBV0005343/1978-07-01 |title=Verdrag tussen het Koninkrijk der Nederlanden en de Bondsrepubliek Duitsland tot [...] van de samenwerking in de Eemsmonding (Eems-Dollardverdrag), 's-Gravenhage, 08-04-1960 |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Government of the Netherlands]] |date=1 July 1978 |accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref> Around 2011, the [[territorial dispute]] gained relevance with plans for the [[Borkum Riffgat]] [[offshore wind farm]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spitsnieuws.nl/archives/binnenland/2011/01/nederland_en_duitsland_besprek.html |title=Nederland en Duitsland bespreken zeegrens |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Spits (newspaper)|Spits]] |date=14 January 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114223131/http://www.spitsnieuws.nl/archives/binnenland/2011/01/nederland_en_duitsland_besprek.html |archivedate=14 January 2011}}</ref> The question about use and administration of the [[territorial waters]] between 3 and 12 [[nautical mile]]s (where the wind farm is located) was settled with another treaty in 2014 by defining a "line", while the border dispute itself remained unresolved.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://zoek.officielebekendmakingen.nl/trb-2014-182.html |title=Verdrag tussen het Koninkrijk der Nederlanden en de Bondsrepubliek Duitsland betreffende het gebruik en beheer van de territoriale zee van 3 tot 12 zeemijlen; (met gemeenschappelijke verklaring en briefwisseling) Op de Eems, 24 oktober 2014 |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Government of the Netherlands]] |date=24 October 2014 |accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref>
==Literature== * K. Essink (ed.), [http://www.verdronkengeschiedenis.nl/nl/stormvloed/stormvloed.html#symposium ''Stormvloed 1509. Geschiedenis van de Dollard''], Groningen: Stichting Verdronken Geschiedenis 2013 ([http://www.verdronkengeschiedenis.nl/nl/stormvloed/stormvloed.html#symposium online]) * O.S. Knottnerus, 'Reclamations and submerged lands in the Ems River Estuary (900-1500)'. In: Erik Thoen et al. (eds.), ''Landscapes or seascapes?. The history of the coastal environment in the North Sea area reconsidered'', Turnhout 2013, S. 241-266. * Gozewinus Acker Stratingh und G.A. Venema, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=9H8AAAAAcAAJ De Dollard of geschied,- aardrijks- en natuurkundige beschrijving van dezen boezem der Eems]'', Groningen 1855, repr. 1979 * [[Frank Westerman]]: ''De graanrepubliek''. Atlas, Amsterdam/Antwerpen 1999, erweitert 2009. [Deutsche Ausgabe ''Das Getreideparadies.'' Ch. Links, Berlin 2009, {{ISBN|978-3-86153-550-8}}.]
