{{Infobox artwork | title = Lumír and Píseň | painting_alignment = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = Czech | other_title_2 = Lumír a Píseň | image = File:Prague, Czech Republic, April 2016 - 454.jpg | image_upright = | alt = | caption = The sculpture in 2016 | artist = [[Josef Václav Myslbek]] | catalogue = | year = | completion_date = <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | type = Sculpture | material = | subject = | height_metric = <!-- (i.e. in metric units) --> | width_metric = | length_metric = | diameter_metric = | height_imperial = <!-- (i.e. in imperial units) --> | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | diameter_imperial = | dimensions = | dimensions_ref = | metric_unit = cm <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | imperial_unit = in <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | condition = | city = Prague, Czech Republic | museum = | accession = | coordinates = {{coord|50|3|50.12|N|14|25|2.69|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | pushpin_map = Czechia Prague Central | pushpin_map_caption = Location in Prague | owner = | preceded_by = <!-- preceding work by the same artist --> | followed_by = <!-- next work by the same artist --> | website = <!-- Official webpage/site only: {{URL|example.com}} --> }} '''''Lumír and Píseň''''' (Czech: '''''Lumír a Píseň''''') is an outdoor sculpture made by [[Josef Václav Myslbek]] in 1889-1897 for [[Palacký Bridge]]. Damaged from [[1945 Bombing of Prague|American bombing]] on February 14, 1945, statues were removed in 1948 in connection with the bridge reconstruction and installed at Vyšehradské sady in [[Vyšehrad]], Prague, Czech Republic.<ref name="praguecityline">{{cite web|url=http://www.praguecityline.cz/prazske-pamatky/sochy-a-sousosi-na-vysehrade-i|title=Sochy a sousoší na Vyšehradě I.|publisher=praguecityline.cz|accessdate=2016-04-30}}</ref><ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Prague: A Cultural and Literary History|author1=Richard Burton|author2=Burton, R.D.E.|date=2003|publisher=Signal Books|isbn=9781902669632|url=https://books.google.cz/books?id=G0uaU8M2bosC&pg=PA81|page=81|accessdate=2016-04-30}}</ref> The statue was previously at the New Town's side of [[Vltava]] and it was installed in the gardens with two other statues from the opposite [[Smíchov]]'s side. The fourth statue, [[Libuše and Přemysl]], was heavily damaged and repaired until reinstalled with the other three in 1977.<ref>[http://www.prague.eu/cs/objekt/mista/562/vysehradske-sady?back=1 Vyšehradské sady] Prague.eu - oficiální turistický portál Prahy.</ref>.
It depicts the legendary bard Lumír and Píseň ("song"). According to [[Manuscripts of Dvůr Králové and Zelená Hora|Queen's Court manuscript]] Lumír refused to sing a hymn for the winners of [[The Maidens' War]], and sings instead his last song to the Vyšehrad, then breaks his instrument. Albeit lucking authenticity, the story was in the 19th century considered a symbol of national conscience.
